[1] Kyrgyzstan (Jalal-Abad Province)
Date: Tue 21 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IRIN News [edited]
<http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?
ReportID=51832&SelectRegion=Asia&SelectCountry=KYRGYZSTAN>

Kyrgyzstan: Typhoid cases reported in south
-------------------------------------------
5 patients have been hospitalized in southern Kyrgyzstan with typhoid
in a town near radioactive dump sites.
"8 local residents have been hospitalized over
the past week in the Mailuu-Suu town in the
southern province of Jalal-Abad, and we have 5
confirmed cases, the rest are ordinary diarrhea
instances," officials at a local sanitary and
epidemiological surveillance center said from
Jalal-Abad on Mon 20 Feb 2006. "All of them are
residents of the upper area of Mailuu-Suu known
as Koktash settlement," they added.
With a population of some 25 000, Mailuu-Suu, 100
km northwest of the provincial capital
Jalal-Abad, is known for its radioactive uranium
dumps, a legacy of the Soviet Union's uranium
mining program in the area.
Local doctors cite contaminated water as the
source of infection. Paramedics in the area are
currently busy looking for other residents who
had been in contact with those already diagnosed
with the disease. Their number is some 260,
according to local doctors.
"Generally, typhoid cases surface during hot
summer months, but in this case, it happened
right in the middle of winter," town mayor
Bumayram Mamaseitova said. "There is a constant
and acute lack of clean drinking water in
Koktash. We had been supplying drinking water to
residents there by trucks both in summer and
autumn. However, our local budget cannot carry
that burden anymore, while the local population
does not want to pay for water," she explained.
"The main issue is the reconstruction of the
town's water supply and sewage networks, which
were installed some 60 years ago. The networks
have become antiquated and run down since then,"
local experts explained, adding that frequent
leakages in the system were the source of water
contamination.
--
